<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1914-02-14T17:00:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1914-02-14T17:00:00-05:00" n="386" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d386">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">File No. 822.00/340.</note>
                        <head>
                            <hi rend="italic">The <gloss type="from">Acting Secretary of
                                    State</gloss> to Consul General <persName type="to">Goding</persName>.</hi>
                        </head>
                        <opener>
                            <seg rendition="#center">[Telegram.]</seg>
                        </opener>
                        <opener>
                            <dateline rendition="#right">
                                <placeName>
                                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Department of State</hi>, <lb/>
                                    <hi rend="italic">Washington</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1914-02-14T17:00:00-05:00">
                                    <hi rend="italic">February 14, 1914, 5 p.m.</hi>
                                </date>
                            </dateline>
                        </opener>
                        <p>Your February 13, 10 a.m. Department desires reports regarding revolution
                            in the north or possible revolutionary movement in Guayaquil when, in
                            your judgment, these are important. Press reports defeat of two thousand
                            Government troops in Manabi. Do you confirm this?</p>
                        <closer>
                            <signed>
                                <hi rend="smallcaps">Moore</hi></signed>.</closer>
                    </div>
                    </body></text></TEI>